      day: 4,
      title: 'Day 4: Release Your Pain',
      reading: `<p><em>“Pain is inevitable. Suffering is optional.”</em></p>
<p>The fourth step in healing is to release your pain. This means acknowledging and accepting the pain you’re feeling, and then letting it go. It’s not about suppressing it or fighting it — it’s about allowing it to flow through you.</p>
<p>You might feel angry, sad, anxious, or numb. This is your body’s way of processing the trauma. It’s not a sign of weakness. It’s a sign of strength.</p>
<p>The most common mistake? Fighting your pain. When we resist what we feel, we store pain inside and feed the part of us that wants to self-sabotage.</p>
<p>Your first step today is to acknowledge that you need to let go of the pain. You can’t heal if you’re holding onto it. You can’t move forward if you’re stuck in the past.</p>
<p>If you’re feeling angry, write down the source of your anger. If you’re feeling sad, write down the memories that bring up sadness. If you’re feeling anxious, write down the triggers. Write it all down. Let it out.</p>
<p>Then, let it go. Release it. Don’t carry it with you. It’s not yours to keep. It’s yours to let go.</p>
<p>Remember: pain is temporary. Healing is permanent. You can’t control the past, but you can control how you respond to it.</p>`,
